The idea of trying to f=
orce a cause effect relation to everything is an inherent tendency of the m=
ind. It is not necessarily how things are. Neither is it useful.

If a man =
wants to only experience God, then every life-experience, apparently good o=
r apparently bad, is only going to take your forward towards the goal if yo=
u keep your aim fixed. No wonder Lord Krishna stresses so much on detachmen=
t and equanimity in his advice to Arjuna, rather than trying to find out ca=
use-effect relationships of the apparently good or the apparently bad kinds=
. 

Sufferings are a great way of focusing on God. Really. Slowly but surel=
y you realize that the world will run in its own pattern and you cannot do =
much about it, except control what is in your power to control, that is you=
r internal state. 

